  "title": "The Three Sounds of '-ED'",
  "learningGoal": "The learner will master the three distinct phonetic realizations of the regular past tense '-ed' suffix (/t/, /d/, /ɪd/), eliminating the common L1 interference of pronouncing every suffix as a heavy /ed/ syllable.",
  "difficultyLevel": "beginner",
  "baseLanguage": "hi",
  "targetLanguage": "en",
  "estimatedTime": 45,
  "prerequisites": ["en_hi_M2B3_lesson_001"],
  "instructions": "In English, the letters '-ED' at the end of a past word can trick you! It DOES NOT always sound like 'एड' (-ed). Sometimes it sounds like a sharp 'T' (Walk-T). Sometimes it sounds like a soft 'D' (Play-D). It only sounds like an extra syllable 'ID' if the word already ends in a T or D! Listen carefully.",
  "contentItems": [
    {
      "type": "note",
      "text": "CRITICAL: Do not say 'Play-Ed'. Say it as one beat: 'Playd'."
    }
  ],
